text: Based on a true story. Everyone knows about her, she's even mentioned in some history books. My grandmother heard stories about  her as a kid.    -I heard a story about a police officer in Corpus Christi who picked up a frantic woman crying by the beach, she was taken back to the police station for questioning about her kids she was crying over, (the officer thought her kids had drowned in the water or something) and the station could hear everything over the radio as the officer was calling it in, the scary thing was,  that by the time the officer made it back to the station the woman had stopped crying and when the officer had looked in the backseat she was gone.    Scared the police officer so bad he ended up quitting his job.

text: My froshmen year I moved to Safford Az, from Cali and they had this legend. She drowned her kids by the river or some shit... crys over what shes done, haunting the bridge at night. We would always taunt the ghost as something to do after drinkin or just to mess around ( not much to do in a small town apparently),.. trying to get our doors to unlock, or spot a glimpse. I always knew the original story was based in Mexico, so I never thought much of it. One night however, after taunting it, my  friend had to drive over that same bridge to go home. She ended up rolling her car just pass the bridge, trying to avoid what she claimed to be a crazy woman running at full speed towards her. She was so terrified that she even started to run from the crash immediately afterwards. I remember the funny thing was, at school when we were all talking about it-checkn out her scrapes and bruises, someone had mentioned that it was the ghost getting revenge. She gave us all a scared look as if she hadn't even considered it and said " After i dropped you guys off I was just tired and ready for bed... I forgot we even went out there"   Nobody really believed her of course, including myself....but I also never took that road at night again.

The 1 I heard when told the stories & in my incident were scarier blood curdling & spine tingling. This sounds generic & sounds like a non Mexican national saying it. Might sound like I'm nit picking but authenticity plays a big factor for me so also the fact that it's in English is also a let down or at least have it in English but takes plays in lil towns next to rivers/lakes or any body of water not an ocean or sea. text: This is a very old Aztec story told for many generations so for people that say (itâ€™s not only Mexican) sorry to disappoint you but IT IS! We were Aztecs and other indigenous peoples before we were converted into Mexicans by Spain. The story takes place in Mexico. Other Latin American countries may have heard about the story and know about it but not every Latin American country has their own â€œLa Lloronaâ€ thereâ€™s only one version and one story that took place in Mexico during indigenous and spaniard times. Also, growing up with this story as a kid I was often told that this woman could be anywhere by any lake in any Mexican neighborhood and heard old people and elders always telling us stories about how they heard her and experienced her. Iâ€™m sorry but as a kid that never made sense to me it! Honestly those experiences by older people either had to be their own fears from childhood manifesting or another spirit of a similar nature. Spirits know how to manipulate and if they know youâ€™re scared of â€œLa Lloronaâ€ they can take that form to scare you into thinking itâ€™s someone itâ€™s not. The actual crime committed by â€œLa Lloronaâ€ took place in Mexico. Psychic Mediums and even paranormal investigators agree that when a ghost haunts, they always haunt the place in which the event took place and no where else. Due to the trauma from the experience they have no ability to travel to multiple places because they are so fixed on the location where the event happens reliving it over and over again. If I went to the town where La Llorona died and killed her children and heard these stories of people seeing her and experiencing her often then Iâ€™d be more inclined to believe it since this is where it took place. However these nutjobs all across the US whoâ€™ve claimed she is literally everywhere by every lake arenâ€™t really fooling me. Donâ€™t mistake ancient folklore with your own childhood fears and donâ€™t allow yourself to be deceived so easily by other energies that feel similar because like I said when a ghost is earthbound they stay where the incident happened and nowhere else! Iâ€™ve even seen Mexican parents straight up lie about their experiences with La Llorona just to have control of their kids only later admitting they lied and just used the story their grandma or mom told them. This just further validates that Mexicans from the states twist this story so much to they point where itâ€™s starting to lose its folklore value as a good genuine folk tale.

text: I think this is the story my mom told me about Honduras , growing up as a child becomes itâ€™s a very well known Folktale , which also ties into certain parts of Central America including Mexico.... A long time a ago ,  a teenage couple fell madly in love  The Girl was 15 and so was the boy I think , And since the boy had an outstanding reputation of hard work and practiced Religion, Her family immediately accepted  Unfortunately, the day they were supposed to get married , it had to be stopped due to a lack of paperwork over baptism or something , Which was a requirement in that country I guess  So the girl went crazy eventually  And never ended up taking the wedding dress off , She wore it everyday  The boy overtime grew hopeless , in marrying her ,due to the Circumstances and one day ended up marrying someone else  ,the way she found out was overhearing one of the villagers talk about it . She then jumped off a near by cliff and committed suicide. She died and her ghost remained on earth looking for her loved one after taking her own life.  Legend says that at night ,in the same spot  She can be seen in a beautiful image  Luring any guy who feels attracted to her into her boundary, only to then turn to something completely horrifying, to eventually kill or traumatize who ever chose to walk up to her that night

text: Oh great. A Mexican version of "The Nun."  You need more than "Dead woman scary" for a horror film. Scary visuals make for a good horror SCENE, but two hours of scary scenes isn't a damn horror movie. What we have in The Nun and movies like it are more accurately described as Terror films. Horror movies need layers of lore that leave one considering and reconsidering the choices and consequences of the movies characters. Horror movies are ULTIMATELY about action and consequence. Terror is an ELEMENT of horror films, and represent consequence.

text: I saw her when i was about 6 yrs old at the Guadalupe river, my whole family went camping at the river, it was about 10 of my cousins and sister running around the river bank, i think we were playing tag. It was night time and there were stars out, on the other side of the river was this huge cliff wall, well i remember hearing someone crying by the river, so most of my cousins ran down to the river to see who got hurt, when i got to the river I looked up to my right and about 150' away I saw a woman glowing a whitish blue floating ontop of the water looking at us, she was wearing a gown and it looked old. Me and my sister saw her, and im sure alot of other cousins saw her and we ran back towards the camp all screaming. Im 26yrs old now, and I am scared to go near any bodies of water at night by myself, this was 20yrs ago and it was either la llorona or some extreme prank with someone floating ontop of the water with a led glowing dress in the middle of nowhere.  I honestly think that if you really want to see her, you would probably have to be a kid, and get someone to cry down by the river at night, I dont recommend it and ive heard ghosts cant harm you but idk she seems evil. Im not sure why I saw her at the guadalupe river but here is a image of what the river with the cliff looks like if your interested, https://www.google.com/search?q=guadalupe+river&source=lnms&tbm=isch&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjx7fPDvqDeAhWQw4MKHZ2AAKQQ_AUIDygC&biw=2560&bih=1336#imgrc=cZrQEZ0qJoUbJM:

text: SERIO SERIO YO LA MIRE' WHEN I WAS 13 in 1982....Me & my best friend (My age)& my carnalita(sister)6 yrs old went to the river(serio im not lying)we were standing over the bridge here in Chimayo northern New Mexico(famous for the Santaurio church,where people walk to every Good Friday)..Me y my b.f. were smoking mota(weed) watching the water go under the bridge(where it feel as if the bridge is moving instead of the water...bueno so anyways, i heard i faint EERIE CRY FAR FAR AWAY...I asked them,"Did u guyz hear that eerie cry",my b.f. said "No,ur just stoned",so i thought ya its just me....CHALE' ALA FREGADA, como 20 seconds later we ALL HEARD IT,as if right next to us. We all took off running  a madre,my sister cudnt catch up,she had to hang on to my b.f. leg.My b.f. dragged her as she ran herself..As we got over a little hill there was a ditch we had to cross over with barbed wire fence over it...as i held the fence up for them to cross over the ditch we  looked up back towards the  river were we were at & we saw a shape of a long door that looked like a cloud or like fog(like a veil of a bride) floating towards us as the eerie cry continued...we passed my dad who was hoeing his garden..He told us ,"por que coren' asina pendejas"(why you girls running fast like dummies)We didn't say anything to him..He then knew why & saw & heard la llorona  too. He suddenly dropped his hoe & ran too..we ran into our adobe home & locked the door,my dad ran into his casita de la noria'(water well tool shack)..Thats an experience I'LL NEVER EVER FORGET!!!Ive also seen UFO's & 1 tht was next to my bedroom window that woke me,i think i was about to be abducted, but that's a different story for a different video...Thank you for reading...and NO I DIDN'T MAKE THIS UP, THIS REALLY HAPPENED ~*PLEASE DO NOT TAKE CREDIT & RECOMMENT MY COMMENT,IT HAPPENED TO ME*~ God Bless,âš˜

Then a women in a white dress started walking across the street. The adult told the kids and my grandma to run back to their friends house. And they stayed there for the night. If any of you guys are interested in the story of la lororna, id be happy to tell you.

text: Judging for what I've just saw in this trailer I can say is a VERY BAD production with a VERY BAD plot.  This is a very old Mexican folk tale, thus the movie should be darker and less predictable, it should be filmed in Mexico, or at least south of the border.  La Llorona is supposed to be a mysterious beautiful woman, sinister, and crying for the loss of her children that she herself drowned in a river.  Her story should be more dramatic than horrific, and her spectre looks like a phantom of delight to attract children in order to make them go to her, not this ugly monster they put in this bad movie.  De plano, these people have modernized la Llorona so much is not even scary.

Of course now I understand that the stories were to make sure we came back from playing out near the wilderness before the sun came down .  Unfortunately because of the stories, I had a lot of nightmares growing up  which ironically has turned me into a major horror movie fan so I canâ€™t wait to see this movie. text: As  Mexican, i should say that La Llorona is not about the Tipical grotesque faces that appears in Hollywood horror movies; Its more about psychological terror. It's Like the horror of Edgar Alan Poe or  Guy de Mauppasant. La llorona is not almost shown, her  deafening causes a chill, or a paralyzing fear. she is heard in rural environments, Lost towns between the mountains where the techonology has not arrived. She walks near dry rivers, beause according to prehispÃ¡nics legends her children drown in a river. First a shrill scream is heard in the distance, but then it becomes sharper, and sharper; And it gives you the impression that is approaching you. But she never arrives.  The absolute darkness, the wind noise, the cries of la llorona who burst unexpectedly are elements that create the perfect fear.
